==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sandjan'', from Indo-European ''*s(w)ent-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[senda]], Old Saxon [[sendian]] (Dutch [[zenden]]), Old High German ''sendan'' (German [[senden]]), Old Norse [[senda]] (Swedish [[sända]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌰𐌽𐌳𐌾𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Welsh [[hynt]] ‘path’, Lithuanian [[siusti]] ‘send’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'sendan/

===Verb===
'''sendan''' (class 1 weak)
# to [[send]]
#:''Ða sende se cyng to þam flotan Leofsig ealdorman'': then the king sent alderman Leofsig to the fleet.  (''Anglo-Saxon Chronicles'')

